    {
      "id": "f8581b75-8d6d-46d4-a7b5-2af36532ddcf",
      "url": "/doc/adr-007-keep-timeline-rendering-client-side-Kc3gc7IyEU",
      "urlId": "Kc3gc7IyEU",
      "title": "ADR 007: Keep timeline rendering client-side",
      "text": "# ADR 007: Keep timeline rendering client-side\n\n## Status\n\nAccepted\n\n## Context\n\nThe timeline view renders a large, frequently-changing list of scheduled events. Early prototypes considered moving timeline layout computation to the server so clients stay thin. However, our SwiftUI clients need frame-accurate, animated repositioning as users scrub or filter the timeline, and round-tripping every layout change to the server would add latency that breaks the scrubbing interaction.\n\n## Decision\n\nTimeline rendering, including layout, filtering, and animation, stays entirely client-side in SwiftUI. The server only supplies raw event data (start/end, metadata); it never computes rendering geometry or view state. Any debug/inspector tooling for the timeline must also run client-side against the same view-model the production timeline uses, so debug output reflects real client behavior.\n\n## Consequences\n\n* Client bundle carries the layout logic; server stays a thin data source.\n* Any new timeline-adjacent screen (including debug/inspector views) must consume the existing client-side view-model rather than re-deriving layout from raw server data.\n* If we later need server-side rendering for other platforms, this ADR must be revisited.",
      "icon": null,
      "color": null,
      "tasks": {
        "completed": 0,
        "total": 0
      },
      "language": "en",
      "createdAt": "2026-07-10T19:38:31.995Z",
